WEBVTT

0
00:00:11.539 --> 00:00:13.539
Understanding adverse childhood experiences,

1
00:00:13.699 --> 00:00:14.260
ACEs.

2
00:00:15.159 --> 00:00:17.299
What are adverse childhood experiences?

3
00:00:17.719 --> 00:00:19.229
Adverse childhood experiences,

4
00:00:19.440 --> 00:00:21.079
often referred to as ACEs,

5
00:00:21.389 --> 00:00:24.520
are traumatic or highly stressful events that occur during childhood,

6
00:00:24.760 --> 00:00:26.739
typically before the age of 18.

7
00:00:27.399 --> 00:00:31.280
These experiences can significantly affect a child's emotional development,

8
00:00:31.520 --> 00:00:32.360
physical health,

9
00:00:32.720 --> 00:00:33.349
relationships,

10
00:00:33.360 --> 00:00:35.779
and behavior throughout their life.

11
00:00:39.290 --> 00:00:42.650
ACEs were first identified through the Adverse Childhood

12
00:00:42.650 --> 00:00:45.909
Experiences Study conducted by the Centers for Disease Control

13
00:00:46.209 --> 00:00:47.130
and Prevention,

14
00:00:47.470 --> 00:00:48.360
CDC

15
00:00:48.610 --> 00:00:51.369
and Kaiser Permanente in the United States.

16
00:00:51.529 --> 00:00:54.250
The study revealed a powerful connection between.

17
00:00:54.444 --> 00:00:56.674
Childhood trauma and long-term health,

18
00:00:56.794 --> 00:00:57.674
mental health,

19
00:00:57.915 --> 00:00:59.075
and social outcomes.

20
00:00:59.395 --> 00:01:02.555
Children who experience multiple ACEs are statistically

21
00:01:02.555 --> 00:01:04.904
more likely to face difficulties in education,

22
00:01:05.275 --> 00:01:05.955
relationships,

23
00:01:06.315 --> 00:01:07.474
emotional regulation,

24
00:01:07.595 --> 00:01:09.355
and physical health later in life.

25
00:01:11.470 --> 00:01:14.260
The types of adverse childhood experiences.

26
00:01:14.669 --> 00:01:19.110
Adverse childhood experiences generally fall into three broad areas

27
00:01:19.389 --> 00:01:20.129
abuse,

28
00:01:20.250 --> 00:01:20.980
neglect,

29
00:01:21.180 --> 00:01:22.650
and household dysfunction.

30
00:01:23.190 --> 00:01:24.449
Abuse may include physical,

31
00:01:24.790 --> 00:01:25.250
emotional,

32
00:01:25.300 --> 00:01:27.610
or sexual harm directed toward a child.

33
00:01:28.449 --> 00:01:30.989
Neglect can involve both emotional neglect,

34
00:01:31.389 --> 00:01:33.370
where a child's emotional needs are not met,

35
00:01:33.610 --> 00:01:34.870
and physical neglect,

36
00:01:35.169 --> 00:01:36.750
where basic needs such as food,

37
00:01:36.970 --> 00:01:37.209
care,

38
00:01:37.360 --> 00:01:40.709
supervision or safety are not adequately provided.

39
00:01:41.050 --> 00:01:42.190
Household dysfunction

40
00:01:42.330 --> 00:01:43.569
refers to environments.

41
00:01:43.675 --> 00:01:48.355
Children are exposed to instability or distressing experiences within the home.

42
00:01:48.535 --> 00:01:50.144
This may include domestic violence,

43
00:01:50.235 --> 00:01:51.775
parental substance misuse,

44
00:01:52.035 --> 00:01:53.375
parental mental illness,

45
00:01:53.714 --> 00:01:55.514
criminal behavior in the household,

46
00:01:55.705 --> 00:01:57.025
parental separation,

47
00:01:57.035 --> 00:01:58.915
or the imprisonment of a parent.

48
00:01:59.819 --> 00:02:01.940
Children who grow up in environments where these

49
00:02:01.940 --> 00:02:05.379
experiences occur frequently may live under constant stress,

50
00:02:05.580 --> 00:02:08.800
which can have a significant effect on their developing brain.